<validation>
1. Demonstrate payment bypass (successful checkout with $0 or manipulated amount)
2. Show webhook manipulation (fake event processed without signature)
3. Prove price manipulation (checkout with wrong/lower price)
4. Document race condition (concurrent operations violate business logic)
5. Show idempotency bypass (duplicate operations processed)
6. Provide reproducible API calls/requests
7. Include webhook payload examples
8. Show before/after account/transaction states
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Amount validation on server side (use Price objects, not raw amounts)
- Webhook signature verification enforced
- Idempotency keys required and validated
- Price IDs validated against database
- Race conditions prevented with database locks
- Metadata not trusted for business logic
- Client-side data never trusted
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Payment bypass (free products/services)
- Account credit manipulation
- Unauthorized refunds
- Subscription fraud
- Data integrity violations
- Financial loss
- Accounting inconsistencies
- Double-charging/billing errors
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Never trust client-sent amounts—use Price objects
2. Always verify webhook signatures with webhook secret
3. Use idempotency keys for all mutating operations
4. Validate price IDs against your database
5. Check for race conditions in balance/credit systems
6. Test with actual Stripe test mode accounts
7. Monitor for unusual patterns (repeated trials, high refunds)
8. Implement rate limiting on payment endpoints
9. Log all payment operations for audit trail
10. Use Stripe's recommended integration patterns
11. Test webhook replay resistance
12. Validate metadata is not used for business logic
13. Check subscription cancellation revokes access
14. Test trial period manipulations
15. Monitor for dispute patterns per user
</pro_tips>

<remember>Stripe security depends on proper server-side validation. Client-side data (amounts, prices, quantities) should never be trusted. Webhooks must have signature verification—no exceptions. Idempotency keys prevent duplicate operations but must be required and validated. Race conditions in payment flows can lead to balance manipulation. Price IDs should be validated against your database, not accepted blindly. Test mode vs production keys are critical—exposing production keys is catastrophic. Metadata is for display only, never for authorization decisions. Always test as if the attacker controls the entire client.</remember>
</stripe_payment_flaws_guide>
